{{use dmy dates|date=July 2018}} {{EngvarB|date=July 2018}} {{Infobox officeholder |honorific-prefix = [[The Honourable|Hon.]] |name = Abdul Majeed Merza |native_name = |native_name_lang = |honorific-suffix = |image = |imagesize = |constituency_MP = [[Kalmunai Electoral District|Kalmunai]] |parliament = Ceylonese |majority = |term_start = 1952 |term_end = 1956 |predecessor = [[M. S. Kariapper]] |successor = [[M. S. Kariapper]] |birth_date = <!---{{Birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|df=yes}}---> |birth_place = |death_date = |death_place = |citizenship = |nationality = |party = [[Independent politician]] |otherparty = |spouse = |partner = |relations = |children = |residence = |alma_mater = |occupation = |profession = |website = |footnotes = }}
'''Abdul Majeed Merza''' was a Ceylonese Muslim businessman and politician.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.lk/members-of-parliament/directory-of-past-members/viewMember/2469|title=Hon. Merza, Abdul Majeed, M.P.|publisher=[[Parliament of Sri Lanka]]|accessdate=20 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|title=Members of the Legislatures of Ceylon: 1931-1972|publisher=[[Parliament of Sri Lanka]]|author=National State Assembly Library|date=1972|page=98}}</ref>
Merza ran as an [[Independent politician|Independent]] at the [[Ceylonese parliamentary election, 1952|2nd parliamentary election]], held between 24 May 1952 and 30 May 1952, in the [[Kalmunai Electoral District|Kalmunai electorate]]. He won the seat, polling 6,078 votes (43% of the total vote), defeating the sitting [[United National Party]] member, [[M. S. Kariapper]] by 3,908 votes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.slelections.gov.lk/web/images/pdf/general-election-results/general-election-1952.pdf |title=Result of Parliamentary General Election 1952 |publisher=Department of Elections, Sri Lanka |accessdate=4 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|title=The Ceylon Historical Journal|volume=2|author=Tisara Prakasakayo|date=1952|page=168}}</ref>
Merza didn't contest his seat at the [[Ceylonese parliamentary election, 1956|1956 parliamentary election]] and was appointed to the board of the [[Valaichchenai Paper Mill|Valaichchenai Paper Corporation]], where he subsequently became the corporation's chairman for a number of years.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Parliamentary Debates: Official Report|volume=85|publisher=Ceylon Government Press|author=[[Parliament of Ceylon]]|date=1969|page=391}}</ref>
