'''Ebenezer "Eben" Allen''' (15 November 1868 – 20 May 1931) was an Australian businessman and politician who was a member of the [[Western Australian Legislative Assembly|Legislative Assembly]] of [[Western Australia]] from 1911 to 1917, representing the [[Electoral district of West Perth|seat of West Perth]].

Allen was born in [[Adelaide]], [[South Australia]], to Mary Selina (née Cant) and Joseph Allen. He attended Glenelg Grammar School (run by [[F. I. Caterer]]), and after leaving school worked for various Adelaide firms. Allen married Effie Marian Conigrave in 1895 (with whom he later had two children), and in 1899 moved to Western Australia to work for her father, [[J. Fairfax Conigrave]]. He eventually went into business on his own, as an auctioneer, real estate agent, and shipping agent. He became secretary of the [[Perth Chamber of Commerce]], and was also a director of a local [[building society]]. Allen served on the [[City of Perth|Perth City Council]] from 1904 to 1912 and again from 1915 to 1918. He first ran for parliament at the 1908 [[Western Australian Legislative Council|Legislative Council]] elections, but lost to [[Arthur Jenkins (Australian politician)|Arthur Jenkins]] in [[Metropolitan Province]].<ref name="bio">[http://www.parliament.wa.gov.au/parliament/library/MPHistoricalData.nsf/(Lookup)/32491D035B28BD35482577E50028A4FC?OpenDocument Ebenezer Allen] – Biographical Register of Members of the Parliament of Western Australia. Retrieved 4 July 2016.</ref>

At the [[Western Australian state election, 1911|1911 state election]], Allen was elected to parliament running for the newly formed [[Western Australian Liberal Party (1911–1917)|Liberal Party]]. He replaced the retiring member in West Perth, [[Thomas Draper]]. Allen was re-elected at the [[Western Australian state election, 1914|1914 election]], but at the [[Western Australian state election, 1917|1917 election]] was opposed by Draper, who had decided he wished to resume his parliamentary career. Both he and Draper stood for the [[Nationalist Party of Australia|Nationalist Party]], which had been created earlier in the year, but Draper was more popular, winning back his former seat with 53.3 percent of the [[First preferences|first-preference vote]]. Allen recontested West Perth at the [[Western Australian state election, 1921|1921 election]], but polled only the third-highest number of votes. Draper lost his seat regardless, with the winning candidate, [[Edith Cowan]], becoming the first female member of parliament in Australia.<ref name="res">{{cite book|last=Black|first=David|authorlink=David Black (historian)|last2=Prescott|first2=Valerie|title=Election statistics : Legislative Assembly of Western Australia, 1890-1996|year=1997|publisher=Western Australian Parliamentary History Project and Western Australian Electoral Commission|location=Perth, [W.A.]|isbn=0730984095}}</ref> Allen died in Perth in May 1931, aged 62. He committed suicide by shooting himself in the head on the [[Perth Esplanade]], having had business troubles and been in poor physical health.<ref>[http://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/83921804 "VALUED CITIZEN PASSES"], ''[[Daily News (Perth, Western Australia)|The Daily News]]'', 20 May 1931.</ref><ref>[http://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/32524742 "MR. EBEN ALLEN'S DEATH."], ''[[The West Australian]]'', 6 June 1931.</ref>

